# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: molecular-docking-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] In biochemistry and molecular biology, a **binding site** is a region on a macromolecule such as a protein that binds to another molecule with specificity.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The binding partner of the macromolecule is often referred to as a ligand.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Ligands may include other proteins (resulting in a protein–protein interaction), enzyme substrates, second messengers, hormones, or allosteric modulators.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The binding event is often, but not always, accompanied by a conformational change that alters the protein's function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Binding to protein binding sites is most often reversible (transient and non-covalent), but can also be covalent reversible or irreversible.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Binding of a ligand to a binding site on protein often triggers a change in conformation in the protein and results in altered cellular function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Hence binding site on protein are critical parts of signal transduction pathways.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Types of ligands include neurotransmitters, toxins, neuropeptides, and steroid hormones.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Binding sites incur functional changes in a number of contexts, including enzyme catalysis, molecular pathway signaling, homeostatic regulation, and physiological function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Electric charge, steric shape and geometry of the site selectively allow for highly specific ligands to bind, activating a particular cascade of cellular interactions the protein is responsible for.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Enzymes incur catalysis by binding more strongly to transition states than substrates and products.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] At the catalytic binding site, several different interactions may act upon the substrate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] These range from electric catalysis, acid and base catalysis, covalent catalysis, and metal ion catalysis.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] These interactions decrease the activation energy of a chemical reaction by providing favorable interactions to stabilize the high energy molecule.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Enzyme binding allows for closer proximity and exclusion of substances irrelevant to the reaction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Side reactions are also discouraged by this specific binding.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Types of enzymes that can perform these actions include oxidoreductases, transferases, hydrolases, lyases, isomerases, and ligases.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] For instance, the transferase hexokinase catalyzes the phosphorylation of glucose to make glucose-6-phosphate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Active site residues of hexokinase allow for stabilization of the glucose molecule in the active site and spur the onset of an alternative pathway of favorable interactions, decreasing the activation energy.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Protein inhibition by inhibitor binding may induce obstruction in pathway regulation, homeostatic regulation and physiological function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Competitive inhibitors compete with substrate to bind to free enzymes at active sites and thus impede the production of the enzyme-substrate complex upon binding.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] For example, carbon monoxide poisoning is caused by the competitive binding of carbon monoxide as opposed to oxygen in hemoglobin.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Uncompetitive inhibitors, alternatively, bind concurrently with substrate at active sites.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Upon binding to an enzyme substrate (ES) complex, an enzyme substrate inhibitor (ESI) complex is formed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Similar to competitive inhibitors, the rate at product formation is decreased also.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Lastly, mixed inhibitors are able to bind to both the free enzyme and the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] However, in contrast to competitive and uncompetitive inhibitors, mixed inhibitors bind to the allosteric site.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Allosteric binding induces conformational changes that may increase the protein's affinity for substrate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] This phenomenon is called positive modulation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Conversely, allosteric binding that decreases the protein's affinity for substrate is negative modulation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] At the active site, a substrate binds to an enzyme to induce a chemical reaction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Substrates, transition states, and products can bind to the active site, as well as any competitive inhibitors.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] For example, in the context of protein function, the binding of calcium to troponin in muscle cells can induce a conformational change in troponin.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] This allows for tropomyosin to expose the actin-myosin binding site to which the myosin head binds to form a cross-bridge and induce a muscle contraction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] In the context of the blood, an example of competitive binding is carbon monoxide which competes with oxygen for the active site on heme.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Carbon monoxide's high affinity may outcompete oxygen in the presence of low oxygen concentration.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] In these circumstances, the binding of carbon monoxide induces a conformation change that discourages heme from binding to oxygen, resulting in carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] At the regulatory site, the binding of a ligand may elicit amplified or inhibited protein function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The binding of a ligand to an allosteric site of a multimeric enzyme often induces positive cooperativity, that is the binding of one substrate induces a favorable conformation change and increases the enzyme's likelihood to bind to a second substrate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Regulatory site ligands can involve homotropic and heterotropic ligands, in which single or multiple types of molecule affects enzyme activity respectively.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Enzymes that are highly regulated are often essential in metabolic pathways.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] For example, phosphofructokinase (PFK), which phosphorylates fructose in glycolysis, is largely regulated by ATP.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Its regulation in glycolysis is imperative because it is the committing and rate limiting step of the pathway.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] PFK also controls the amount of glucose designated to form ATP through the catabolic pathway.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Therefore, at sufficient levels of ATP, PFK is allosterically inhibited by ATP.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] This regulation efficiently conserves glucose reserves, which may be needed for other pathways.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Citrate, an intermediate of the citric acid cycle, also works as an allosteric regulator of PFK.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Binding sites can be characterized also by their structural features.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Recent research shows that binding site structure has profound consequences for the biology of protein complexes (evolution of function, allostery).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Cryptic binding sites are the binding sites that are transiently formed in an apo form or that are induced by ligand binding.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Considering the cryptic binding sites increases the size of the potentially "druggable" human proteome from ~40% to ~78% of disease-associated proteins.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Binding curves describe the binding behavior of ligand to a protein.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Curves can be characterized by their shape, sigmoidal or hyperbolic, which reflect whether or not the protein exhibits cooperative or noncooperative binding behavior respectively.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Typically, the x-axis describes the concentration of ligand and the y-axis describes the fractional saturation of ligands bound to all available binding sites.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The Michaelis Menten equation is usually used when determining the shape of the curve.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The Michaelis Menten equation is derived based on steady-state conditions and accounts for the enzyme reactions taking place in a solution.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] However, when the reaction takes place while the enzyme is bound to a substrate, the kinetics play out differently.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Modeling with binding curves are useful when evaluating the binding affinities of oxygen to hemoglobin and myoglobin in the blood.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Hemoglobin, which has four heme groups, exhibits cooperative binding.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] This means that the binding of oxygen to a heme group on hemoglobin induces a favorable conformation change that allows for increased binding favorability of oxygen for the next heme groups.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] In these circumstances, the binding curve of hemoglobin will be sigmoidal due to its increased binding favorability for oxygen.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Since myoglobin has only one heme group, it exhibits noncooperative binding which is hyperbolic on a binding curve.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Biochemical differences between different organisms and humans are useful for drug development.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] For instance, penicillin kills bacteria by inhibiting the bacterial enzyme DD-transpeptidase, destroying the development of the bacterial cell wall and inducing cell death.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Thus, the study of binding sites is relevant to many fields of research, including cancer mechanisms, drug formulation, and physiological regulation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The formulation of an inhibitor to mute a protein's function is a common form of pharmaceutical therapy.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] In the scope of cancer, ligands that are edited to have a similar appearance to the natural ligand are used to inhibit tumor growth.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] For example, methotrexate, a chemotherapeutic, acts as a competitive inhibitor at the dihydrofolate reductase active site.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] This interaction inhibits the synthesis of tetrahydrofolate, shutting off production of DNA, RNA and proteins.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Inhibition of this function represses neoplastic growth and improves severe psoriasis and adult rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] In cardiovascular illnesses, drugs such as beta blockers are used to treat patients with hypertension.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Beta blockers (β-Blockers) are antihypertensive agents that block the binding of the hormones adrenaline and noradrenaline to β1 and β2 receptors in the heart and blood vessels.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] These receptors normally mediate the sympathetic "fight or flight" response, causing constriction of the blood vessels.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Competitive inhibitors are also largely found commercially.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Botulinum toxin, known commercially as Botox, is a neurotoxin that causes flaccid paralysis in the muscle due to binding to acetylcholine dependent nerves.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] This interaction inhibits muscle contractions, giving the appearance of smooth muscle.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] A number of computational tools have been developed for the prediction of the location of binding sites on proteins.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] These can be broadly classified into sequence based or structure based.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Sequence based methods rely on the assumption that the sequences of functionally conserved portions of proteins such as binding site are conserved.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Structure based methods require the 3D structure of the protein.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] These methods in turn can be subdivided into template and pocket based methods.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Template based methods search for 3D similarities between the target protein and proteins with known binding sites.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] The pocket based methods search for concave surfaces or buried pockets in the target protein that possess features such as hydrophobicity and hydrogen bonding capacity that would allow them to bind ligands with high affinity.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/binding-site] Even though the term pocket is used here, similar methods can be used to predict binding sites used in protein-protein interactions that are usually more planar, not in pockets.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In chemistry, **rotamers** are chemical species that differ from one another primarily due to rotations about one single bond.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Various arrangements of atoms in a molecule that differ by rotation about single bonds can also be referred to as **conformations**.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Conformations, which represent local minima on the potential energy surface, are called **conformers**.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Conformers can differ from one another due to rotation of multiple bonds; rotamers are a subset of conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Conformers/rotamers usually differ little in their energies, so they are almost never separable in a practical sense.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Rotations about single bonds are subject to small energy barriers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] When the time scale for interconversion is long enough for isolation of individual rotamers (usually arbitrarily defined as a half-life of interconversion of 1000 seconds or longer), the species are termed atropisomers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The ring-flip of substituted cyclohexanes constitutes a common form of conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The study of the energetics of bond rotation is referred to as **conformational analysis**.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In some cases, conformational analysis can be used to predict and explain product selectivity, mechanisms, and rates of reactions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Conformational analysis also plays an important role in rational, structure-based drug design.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Rotating their carbon–carbon bonds, the molecules ethane and propane have three local energy minima.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] They are structurally and energetically equivalent, and are called the *staggered conformers*.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For each molecule, the three substituents emanating from each carbon–carbon bond are staggered, with each H–C–C–H dihedral angle (and H–C–C–CH3 dihedral angle in the case of propane) equal to 60° (or approximately equal to 60° in the case of propane).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The three eclipsed conformations, in which the dihedral angles are zero, are transition states (energy maxima) connecting two equivalent energy minima, the staggered conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The butane molecule is the simplest molecule for which single bond rotations result in two types of nonequivalent structures, known as the *anti*- and *gauche-*conformers (see figure).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The energy separation between gauche and anti is 0.9 kcal/mol associated with the strain energy of the gauche conformer.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The anti conformer is, therefore, the most stable (≈ 0 kcal/mol).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The three eclipsed conformations with dihedral angles of 0°, 120°, and 240° are transition states between conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Note that the two eclipsed conformations have distinct energies: at 0° the two methyl groups are eclipsed, resulting in higher energy (≈ 5 kcal/mol) than at 120°, where the methyl groups are eclipsed with hydrogens (≈ 3.5 kcal/mol).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] A rough approximate function can illustrate the main features of the conformational analysis for unbranched linear alkanes with rotation around a central C–C bond (C1–C2 in ethane, C2–C3 in butane, C3–C4 in hexane, etc.).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The members of this series have the general formula C*2n*H*4n+2* with the index *n = 1, 2, 3,* etc.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] It can be assumed that the angle strain is negligible in alkanes since the bond angles are all near the tetrahedral ideal.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The energy profile is thus periodic with $2\pi /3$ (120°) periodicity due to the threefold symmetry of sp3-hybridized carbon atoms.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For alkanes, the dominant term is usually $k=3$ , reflecting the threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Higher terms may be included for precision where steric effects vary.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The primary contribution comes from torsional strain due to alkyl groups eclipsing, captured by the $\cos(3\theta )$ term.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Steric interactions rise with the size of substituents (H– for ethane, CH3– for butane, C2H5– for hexane, etc.), taken into account by the $\cos(\theta )$ term $(k=1)$ .
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The number of carbon atoms clearly influences the size of substituents on the central C–C bond.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In general, for unbranched linear alkanes with even-numbered chains, there will be two C*n-1*H*2n-1* group substituents.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Here $V(\theta ,n)$ is given in kcal/mol and $k=1,3$ .
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] This function largely neglects angle strain and long-range interactions for the n members of the series.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] While simple molecules can be described by these types of conformations, more complex molecules require the use of the Klyne–Prelog system to describe the conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Three isotherms are given in the diagram depicting the equilibrium distribution of two conformers at various temperatures.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] At a free energy difference of 0 kcal/mol, this analysis gives an equilibrium constant of 1, meaning that two conformers exist in a 1:1 ratio.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The two have equal free energy; neither is more stable, so neither predominates compared to the other.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] A negative difference in free energy means that a conformer interconverts to a thermodynamically more stable conformation, thus the equilibrium constant will always be greater than 1.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For example, the Δ*G°* for the transformation of butane from the *gauche* conformer to the *anti* conformer is −0.47 kcal/mol at 298 K.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] This gives an equilibrium constant is about 2.2 in favor of the *anti* conformer, or a 31:69 mixture of *gauche*:*anti* conformers at equilibrium.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Conversely, a positive difference in free energy means the conformer already is the more stable one, so the interconversion is an unfavorable equilibrium (*K* < 1).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The left hand side is the proportion of conformer *i* in an equilibrating mixture of *M* conformers in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] On the right side, *E**k* (*k* = 1, 2, ..., *M*) is the energy of conformer *k*, *R* is the molar ideal gas constant (approximately equal to 8.314 J/(mol·K) or 1.987 cal/(mol·K)), and *T* is the absolute temperature.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The denominator of the right side is the partition function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The effects of electrostatic and steric interactions of the substituents as well as orbital interactions such as hyperconjugation are responsible for the relative stability of conformers and their transition states.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The contributions of these factors vary depending on the nature of the substituents and may either contribute positively or negatively to the energy barrier.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Computational studies of small molecules such as ethane suggest that electrostatic effects make the greatest contribution to the energy barrier; however, the barrier is traditionally attributed primarily to steric interactions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In the case of cyclic systems, the steric effect and contribution to the free energy can be approximated by A values, which measure the energy difference when a substituent on cyclohexane in the axial as compared to the equatorial position.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In large (>14 atom) rings, there are many accessible low-energy conformations which correspond to the strain-free diamond lattice.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The short timescale of interconversion precludes the separation of conformer in most cases.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Atropisomers are conformational isomers which can be separated due to restricted rotation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The equilibrium between conformational isomers can be observed using a variety of spectroscopic techniques.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Protein folding also generates conformers which can be observed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The Karplus equation relates the dihedral angle of vicinal protons to their J-coupling constants as measured by NMR.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The equation aids in the elucidation of protein folding as well as the conformations of other rigid aliphatic molecules.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Protein side chains exhibit rotamers, whose distribution is determined by their steric interaction with different conformations of the backbone.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] This effect is evident from statistical analysis of the conformations of protein side chains in the Backbone-dependent rotamer library.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Conformational dynamics can be monitored by variable temperature NMR spectroscopy.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The technique applies to barriers of 8–14 kcal/mol, and species exhibiting such dynamics are often called "fluxional".
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For example, in cyclohexane derivatives, the two chair conformers interconvert rapidly at room temperature.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The ring-flip proceeds at a rates of approximately 105 ring-flips/sec, with an overall energy barrier of 10 kcal/mol (42 kJ/mol).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] This barrier precludes separation at ambient temperatures.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] However, at low temperatures below the coalescence point one can directly monitor the equilibrium by NMR spectroscopy and by dynamic, temperature dependent NMR spectroscopy the barrier interconversion.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Besides NMR spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy is used to measure conformer ratios.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For the axial and equatorial conformer of bromocyclohexane, νCBr differs by almost 50 cm−1.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Reaction rates are highly dependent on the conformation of the reactants.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In many cases the dominant product arises from the reaction of the *less prevalent* conformer, by virtue of the Curtin-Hammett principle.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] This is typical for situations where the conformational equilibration is much faster than reaction to form the product.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The dependence of a reaction on the stereochemical orientation is therefore usually only visible in configurational analysis, in which a particular conformation is locked by substituents.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Prediction of rates of many reactions involving the transition between sp2 and sp3 states, such as ketone reduction, alcohol oxidation or nucleophilic substitution is possible if all conformers and their relative stability ruled by their strain is taken into account.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] One example where the rotamers become significant is elimination reactions, which involve the simultaneous removal of a proton and a leaving group from vicinal or *anti*periplanar positions under the influence of a base.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The mechanism requires that the departing atoms or groups follow antiparallel trajectories.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For open chain substrates this geometric prerequisite is met by at least one of the three staggered conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] For some cyclic substrates such as cyclohexane, however, an antiparallel arrangement may not be attainable depending on the substituents which might set a conformational lock.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Adjacent substituents on a cyclohexane ring can achieve antiperiplanarity only when they occupy trans diaxial positions (that is, both are in axial position, one going up and one going down).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The thermodynamically unfavored conformation has the *t*-Bu group in the axial position, which is higher in energy by more than 5 kcal/mol (see A value).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] As a result, the *t*-Bu group "locks" the ring in the conformation where it is in the equatorial position and substitution reaction is observed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] On the other hand, *cis*-4-*tert*-butylcyclohexyl chloride undergoes elimination because antiperiplanarity of Cl and H can be achieved when the *t*-Bu group is in the favorable equatorial position.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] isomer can attain antiperiplanarity only via the unfavored axial conformer; therefore, it does not eliminate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] isomer is already in the correct geometry in its most stable conformation; therefore, it eliminates easily.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The repulsion between an axial *t*-butyl group and hydrogen atoms in the 1,3-diaxial position is so strong that the cyclohexane ring will revert to a twisted boat conformation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The strain in cyclic structures is usually characterized by deviations from ideal bond angles (Baeyer strain), ideal torsional angles (Pitzer strain) or transannular (Prelog) interactions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Alkane conformers arise from rotation around sp3 hybridised carbon–carbon sigma bonds.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The smallest alkane with such a chemical bond, ethane, exists as an infinite number of conformations with respect to rotation around the C–C bond.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Two of these are recognised as energy minimum (staggered conformation) and energy maximum (eclipsed conformation) forms.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The existence of specific conformations is due to hindered rotation around sigma bonds, although a role for hyperconjugation is proposed by a competing theory.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The importance of energy minima and energy maxima is seen by extension of these concepts to more complex molecules for which stable conformations may be predicted as minimum-energy forms.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The determination of stable conformations has also played a large role in the establishment of the concept of asymmetric induction and the ability to predict the stereochemistry of reactions controlled by steric effects.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In the example of staggered ethane in Newman projection, a hydrogen atom on one carbon atom has a 60° **torsional angle** or **torsion angle** with respect to the nearest hydrogen atom on the other carbon so that steric hindrance is minimised.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The staggered conformation is more stable by 12.5 kJ/mol than the eclipsed conformation, which is the energy maximum for ethane.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In the eclipsed conformation the torsional angle is minimised.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In butane, the two staggered conformations are no longer equivalent and represent two distinct conformers:the **anti-conformation** (left-most, below) and the **gauche conformation** (right-most, below).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Both conformations are free of torsional strain, but, in the gauche conformation, the two methyl groups are in closer proximity than the sum of their van der Waals radii.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The interaction between the two methyl groups is repulsive (van der Waals strain), and an energy barrier results.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The eclipsed methyl groups exert a greater steric strain because of their greater electron density compared to lone hydrogen atoms.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The textbook explanation for the existence of the energy maximum for an eclipsed conformation in ethane is steric hindrance, but, with a C-C bond length of 154 pm and a Van der Waals radius for hydrogen of 120 pm, the hydrogen atoms in ethane are never in each other's way.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The question of whether steric hindrance is responsible for the eclipsed energy maximum is a topic of debate to this day.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] One alternative to the steric hindrance explanation is based on hyperconjugation as analyzed within the Natural Bond Orbital framework.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In the staggered conformation, one C-H sigma bonding orbital donates electron density to the antibonding orbital of the other C-H bond.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] The energetic stabilization of this effect is maximized when the two orbitals have maximal overlap, occurring in the staggered conformation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] There is no overlap in the eclipsed conformation, leading to a disfavored energy maximum.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] On the other hand, an analysis within quantitative molecular orbital theory shows that 2-orbital-4-electron (steric) repulsions are dominant over hyperconjugation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] A valence bond theory study also emphasizes the importance of steric effects.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Torsional strain or "Pitzer strain" refers to resistance to twisting about a bond.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] In *n*-pentane, the terminal methyl groups experience additional pentane interference.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Replacing hydrogen by fluorine in polytetrafluoroethylene changes the stereochemistry from the zigzag geometry to that of a helix due to electrostatic repulsion of the fluorine atoms in the 1,3 positions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/conformational-isomerism] Evidence for the helix structure in the crystalline state is derived from X-ray crystallography and from NMR spectroscopy and circular dichroism in solution.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In the field of molecular modeling, **docking** is a method which predicts the preferred orientation of one molecule to a second when a ligand and a target are bound to each other to form a stable complex.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Knowledge of the preferred orientation in turn may be used to predict the strength of association or binding affinity between two molecules using, for example, scoring functions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The associations between biologically relevant molecules such as proteins, peptides, nucleic acids, carbohydrates, and lipids play a central role in signal transduction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Furthermore, the relative orientation of the two interacting partners may affect the type of signal produced (e.g., agonism vs antagonism).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Therefore, docking is useful for predicting both the strength and type of signal produced.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Molecular docking is one of the most frequently used methods in structure-based drug design, due to its ability to predict the binding-conformation of small molecule ligands to the appropriate target binding site.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Characterisation of the binding behaviour plays an important role in rational design of drugs as well as to elucidate fundamental biochemical processes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Hence, docking is useful to discover new ligand for a target by screening large virtual compound libraries and as a start for ligand optimization or investigation of mechanism of action.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] One can think of molecular docking as a problem of *"lock-and-key"*, in which one wants to find the correct relative orientation of the *"key"* which will open up the *"lock"* (where on the surface of the lock is the key hole, which direction to turn the key after it is inserted, etc.).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Here, the protein can be thought of as the "lock" and the ligand can be thought of as a "key".
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Molecular docking may be defined as an optimization problem, which would describe the "best-fit" orientation of a ligand that binds to a particular protein of interest.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] However, since both the ligand and the protein are flexible, a *"hand-in-glove"* analogy is more appropriate than *"lock-and-key"*.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] During the course of the docking process, the ligand and the protein adjust their conformation to achieve an overall "best-fit" and this kind of conformational adjustment resulting in the overall binding is referred to as **"induced-fit"**.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Molecular docking research focuses on computationally simulating the molecular recognition process.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] It aims to achieve an optimized conformation for both the protein and ligand and relative orientation between protein and ligand such that the free energy of the overall system is minimized.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Two approaches are particularly popular within the molecular docking community.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Both approaches have significant advantages as well as some limitations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Geometric matching/shape complementarity methods describe the protein and ligand as a set of features that make them dockable.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] These features may include molecular surface/complementary surface descriptors.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In this case, the receptor's molecular surface is described in terms of its solvent-accessible surface area and the ligand's molecular surface is described in terms of its matching surface description.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The complementarity between the two surfaces amounts to the shape matching description that may help finding the complementary pose of docking the target and the ligand molecules.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Another approach is to describe the hydrophobic features of the protein using turns in the main-chain atoms.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Yet another approach is to use a Fourier shape descriptor technique.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Whereas the shape complementarity based approaches are typically fast and robust, they cannot usually model the movements or dynamic changes in the ligand/protein conformations accurately, although recent developments allow these methods to investigate ligand flexibility.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Shape complementarity methods can quickly scan through several thousand ligands in a matter of seconds and actually figure out whether they can bind at the protein's active site, and are usually scalable to even protein-protein interactions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] They are also much more amenable to pharmacophore based approaches, since they use geometric descriptions of the ligands to find optimal binding.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Simulating the docking process is much more complicated.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In this approach, the protein and the ligand are separated by some physical distance, and the ligand finds its position into the protein's active site after a certain number of "moves" in its conformational space.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The moves incorporate rigid body transformations such as translations and rotations, as well as internal changes to the ligand's structure including torsion angle rotations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Each of these moves in the conformation space of the ligand induces a total energetic cost of the system.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Hence, the system's total energy is calculated after every move.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The obvious advantage of docking simulation is that ligand flexibility is easily incorporated, whereas shape complementarity techniques must use ingenious methods to incorporate flexibility in ligands.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Also, it more accurately models reality, whereas shape complementary techniques are more of an abstraction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Clearly, simulation is computationally expensive, having to explore a large energy landscape.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Grid-based techniques, optimization methods, and increased computer speed have made docking simulation more realistic.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] To perform a docking screen, the first requirement is a structure of the protein of interest.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] but can also derive from homology modeling construction or from AlphaFold predictions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] This protein structure and a database of potential ligands serve as inputs to a docking program.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The success of a docking program depends on two components: the search algorithm and the scoring function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The search space in theory consists of all possible orientations and conformations of the protein paired with the ligand.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Most docking programs in use account for the whole conformational space of the ligand (flexible ligand), and several attempt to model a flexible protein receptor.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Each "snapshot" of the pair is referred to as a **pose**.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] A variety of conformational search strategies have been applied to the ligand and to the receptor.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Conformations of the ligand may be generated in the absence of the receptor and subsequently docked or conformations may be generated on-the-fly in the presence of the receptor binding cavity, or with full rotational flexibility of every dihedral angle using fragment based docking.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Force field energy evaluation are most often used to select energetically reasonable conformations, but knowledge-based methods have also been used.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Peptides are both highly flexible and relatively large-sized molecules, which makes modeling their flexibility a challenging task.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] A number of methods were developed to allow for efficient modeling of flexibility of peptides during protein-peptide docking.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Computational capacity has increased dramatically over the last decade making possible the use of more sophisticated and computationally intensive methods in computer-assisted drug design.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] However, dealing with receptor flexibility in docking methodologies is still a thorny issue.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The main reason behind this difficulty is the large number of degrees of freedom that have to be considered in this kind of calculations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Neglecting it, however, in some of the cases may lead to poor docking results in terms of binding pose prediction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Multiple static structures experimentally determined for the same protein in different conformations are often used to emulate receptor flexibility.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Alternatively rotamer libraries of amino acid side chains that surround the binding cavity may be searched to generate alternate but energetically reasonable protein conformations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Docking programs generate a large number of potential ligand poses, of which some can be immediately rejected due to clashes with the protein.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The remainder are evaluated using some scoring function, which takes a pose as input and returns a number indicating the likelihood that the pose represents a favorable binding interaction and ranks one ligand relative to another.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Most scoring functions are physics-based molecular mechanics force fields that estimate the energy of the pose within the binding site.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The components consist of solvent effects, conformational changes in the protein and ligand, free energy due to protein-ligand interactions, internal rotations, association energy of ligand and receptor to form a single complex and free energy due to changes in vibrational modes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] A low (negative) energy indicates a stable system and thus a likely binding interaction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Alternative approaches use modified scoring functions to include constraints based on known key protein-ligand interactions, or knowledge-based potentials derived from interactions observed in large databases of protein-ligand structures (e.g. the Protein Data Bank).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] There are a large number of structures from X-ray crystallography for complexes between proteins and high affinity ligands, but comparatively fewer for low affinity ligands as the latter complexes tend to be less stable and therefore more difficult to crystallize.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Scoring functions trained with this data can dock high affinity ligands correctly, but they will also give plausible docked conformations for ligands that do not bind.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] This gives a large number of false positive hits, i.e., ligands predicted to bind to the protein that actually don't when placed together in a test tube.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] One way to reduce the number of false positives is to recalculate the energy of the top scoring poses using (potentially) more accurate but computationally more intensive techniques such as Generalized Born or Poisson-Boltzmann methods.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The interdependence between sampling and scoring function affects the docking capability in predicting plausible poses or binding affinities for novel compounds.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Thus, an assessment of a docking protocol is generally required (when experimental data is available) to determine its predictive capability.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Docking accuracy represents one measure of a docking program's ability to reproduce the experimentally observed binding pose of a ligand.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Fitness is typically quantified by calculating the root-mean-square deviation (RMSD) of the non-hydrogen atoms between the docked pose and the experimental structure.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] An RMSD value below 2.0 Å is commonly considered indicative of a successful docking model.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] However, because RMSD generally increases with the number of heavy atoms in the ligand, a more permissive cutoff may be appropriate for larger molecules.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Importantly, RMSD alone should not be used to evaluate docking quality.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] A comprehensive assessment should also consider the program's ability to reproduce key ligand–receptor interactions and the plausibility of the generated conformations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] This is particularly relevant when using deep-learning–based molecular docking approaches.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Docking screens can be evaluated based on their ability to enrich known active ligands from a large database of presumed non-binding "decoy" molecules.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In this approach, the performance of a docking protocol is assessed by its capacity to rank a small number of known active compounds within the top fraction of screened molecules, despite the presence of a much larger number of decoys.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The enrichment factor (EF) quantifies this early recognition capability.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Thus, EF compares the fraction of actives retrieved in the top-ranked subset to the fraction expected by random selection.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] An EF value greater than 1 indicates enrichment beyond random performance.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In particular, **EF1%** measures enrichment within the top 1% of the ranked database and is commonly used to evaluate early recognition performance in virtual screening, where identifying active compounds at the very top of the list is especially important.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In addition to EF, the area under the receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve (AUC) is widely used to evaluate screening performance across the entire ranked list.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Resulting hits from docking screens are subjected to pharmacological validation (e.g.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] IC50, affinity or potency measurements).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Only prospective studies constitute conclusive proof of the suitability of a technique for a particular target.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In the case of G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs), which are targets of more than 30% of marketed drugs, molecular docking led to the discovery of more than 500 GPCR ligands.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The potential of docking programs to reproduce binding modes as determined by X-ray crystallography can be assessed by a range of docking benchmark sets.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] For small molecules, several benchmark data sets for docking and virtual screening exist e.g.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] *Astex Diverse Set* consisting of high quality protein−ligand X-ray crystal structures, the *Directory of Useful Decoys* (DUD) for evaluation of virtual screening performance, the *LEADS-FRAG* data set for fragments, and the *LIT-PCBA* data set for machine-learning and virtual screening.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] In addition to dataset development, large-scale comparative assessments have been conducted.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] The Comparative Assessment of Scoring Functions (CASF) provides systematic benchmarking of docking and scoring functions using standardized protein–ligand complexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] CASF evaluates multiple aspects of performance, including docking power (pose prediction), scoring power (binding affinity prediction), ranking power, and screening power.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] Results from CASF studies have highlighted substantial variability among docking programs and scoring functions, emphasizing that no single method consistently outperforms others across all evaluation criteria.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] An evaluation of docking programs for their potential to reproduce peptide binding modes can be assessed by *Lessons for Efficiency Assessment of Docking and Scoring* (LEADS-PEP).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] A binding interaction between a small molecule ligand and an enzyme protein may result in activation or inhibition of the enzyme.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/docking-molecular] If the protein is a receptor, ligand binding may result in agonism or antagonism.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In biochemistry and pharmacology, a **ligand** is a substance that forms a complex with a biomolecule to serve a biological purpose.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The etymology stems from Latin *ligare*, which means 'to bind'.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In protein-ligand binding, the ligand is usually a molecule which produces a signal by binding to a site on a target protein.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The binding typically results in a change of conformational isomerism (conformation) of the target protein.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In DNA-ligand binding studies, the ligand can be a small molecule, ion, or protein which binds to the DNA double helix.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The relationship between ligand and binding partner is a function of charge, hydrophobicity, and molecular structure.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Binding occurs by intermolecular forces, such as ionic bonds, hydrogen bonds and Van der Waals forces.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The association or docking is actually reversible through dissociation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Measurably irreversible covalent bonding between a ligand and target molecule is atypical in biological systems.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In contrast to the definition of ligand in metalorganic and inorganic chemistry, in biochemistry it is ambiguous whether the ligand generally binds at a metal site, as is the case in hemoglobin.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In general, the interpretation of ligand is contextual with regard to what sort of binding has been observed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligand binding to a receptor protein alters the conformation by affecting the three-dimensional shape orientation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The conformation of a receptor protein composes the functional state.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligands include substrates, inhibitors, activators, signaling lipids, and neurotransmitters.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The rate of binding is called affinity, and this measurement typifies a tendency or strength of the effect.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Binding affinity is actualized not only by host–guest interactions, but also by solvent effects that can play a dominant, steric role which drives non-covalent binding in solution.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The solvent provides a chemical environment for the ligand and receptor to adapt, and thus accept or reject each other as partners.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Radioligands are radioisotope labeled compounds used in vivo as tracers in PET studies and for in vitro binding studies.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The interaction of ligands with their binding sites can be characterized in terms of a binding affinity.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In general, high-affinity ligand binding results from greater attractive forces between the ligand and its receptor while low-affinity ligand binding involves less attractive force.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In general, high-affinity binding results in a higher occupancy of the receptor by its ligand than is the case for low-affinity binding; the residence time (lifetime of the receptor-ligand complex) does not correlate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] High-affinity binding of ligands to receptors is often physiologically important when some of the binding energy can be used to cause a conformational change in the receptor, resulting in altered behavior for example of an associated ion channel or enzyme.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] A ligand that can bind to and alter the function of the receptor that triggers a physiological response is called a receptor agonist.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligands that bind to a receptor but fail to activate the physiological response are receptor antagonists.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] High-affinity ligand binding implies that a relatively low concentration of a ligand is adequate to maximally occupy a ligand-binding site and trigger a physiological response.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Receptor affinity is measured by an inhibition constant or Ki value, the concentration required to occupy 50% of the receptor.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligand affinities are most often measured indirectly as an IC50 value from a competition binding experiment where the concentration of a ligand required to displace 50% of a fixed concentration of reference ligand is determined.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The Ki value can be estimated from IC50 through the Cheng Prusoff equation.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligand affinities can also be measured directly as a dissociation constant (Kd) using methods such as fluorescence quenching, isothermal titration calorimetry or surface plasmon resonance.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Low-affinity binding (high Ki level) implies that a relatively high concentration of a ligand is required before the binding site is maximally occupied and the maximum physiological response to the ligand is achieved.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In the example shown to the right, two different ligands bind to the same receptor binding site.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Only one of the agonists shown can maximally stimulate the receptor and, thus, can be defined as a *full agonist*.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] An agonist that can only partially activate the physiological response is called a *partial agonist*.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In this example, the concentration at which the full agonist (red curve) can half-maximally activate the receptor is about 5 × 10−9 Molar (nM = nanomolar).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Binding affinity is most commonly determined using a radiolabeled ligand, known as a tagged ligand.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] *Homologous competitive binding experiments* involve binding competition between a tagged ligand and an untagged ligand.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] MP-SPR also enables measurements in high saline dissociation buffers thanks to a unique optical setup.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Microscale thermophoresis (MST), an immobilization-free method was developed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] This method allows the determination of the binding affinity without any limitation to the ligand's molecular weight.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] For the use of statistical mechanics in a quantitative study of the ligand-receptor binding affinity, see the comprehensive article on the configurational partition function.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Binding affinity data alone does not determine the overall potency of a drug or a naturally produced (biosynthesized) hormone.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Potency is a result of the complex interplay of both the binding affinity and the ligand efficacy.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligand efficacy refers to the ability of the ligand to produce a biological response upon binding to the target receptor and the quantitative magnitude of this response.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] This response may be as an agonist, antagonist, or inverse agonist, depending on the physiological response produced.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Selective ligands have a tendency to bind to very limited kinds of receptor, whereas non-selective ligands bind to several types of receptors.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] This plays an important role in pharmacology, where drugs that are non-selective tend to have more adverse effects, because they bind to several other receptors in addition to the one generating the desired effect.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] PIP2) in complex with a hydrophobic protein (e.g. lipid-gated ion channels) determining the affinity is complicated by non-specific hydrophobic interactions.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Non-specific hydrophobic interactions can be overcome when the affinity of the ligand is high.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] For example, PIP2 binds with high affinity to PIP2 gated ion channels.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Bivalent ligands consist of two drug-like molecules (pharmacophores or ligands) connected by an inert linker.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] There are various kinds of bivalent ligands and are often classified based on what the pharmacophores target.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Homobivalent ligands target two of the same receptor types.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Heterobivalent ligands target two different receptor types.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Bitopic ligands target an orthosteric binding sites and allosteric binding sites on the same receptor.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In scientific research, bivalent ligands have been used to study receptor dimers and to investigate their properties.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] This class of ligands was pioneered by Philip S.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Portoghese and coworkers while studying the opioid receptor system.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Bivalent ligands were also reported early on by Micheal Conn and coworkers for the gonadotropin-releasing hormone receptor.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Since these early reports, there have been many bivalent ligands reported for various G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) systems including cannabinoid, serotonin, oxytocin, and melanocortin receptor systems, and for GPCR-LIC systems (D2 and nACh receptors).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Bivalent ligands usually tend to be larger than their monovalent counterparts, and therefore, not 'drug-like' as in Lipinski's rule of five.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Many believe this limits their applicability in clinical settings.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] In spite of these beliefs, there have been many ligands that have reported successful pre-clinical animal studies.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Given that some bivalent ligands can have many advantages compared to their monovalent counterparts (such as tissue selectivity, increased binding affinity, and increased potency or efficacy), bivalents may offer some clinical advantages as well.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Ligands of proteins can be characterized also by the number of protein chains they bind.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] "Monodesmic" ligands (μόνος: single, δεσμός: binding) are ligands that bind a single protein chain, while "polydesmic" ligands (πολοί: many) are frequent in protein complexes, and are ligands that bind more than one protein chain, typically in or near protein interfaces.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Recent research shows that the type of ligands and binding site structure has profound consequences for the evolution, function, allostery and folding of protein compexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] A privileged scaffold is a molecular framework or chemical moiety that is statistically recurrent among known drugs or among a specific array of biologically active compounds.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] These privileged elements can be used as a basis for designing new active biological compounds or compound libraries.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] The dramatically increased computing power of supercomputers and personal computers has made it possible to study protein–ligand interactions also by means of computational chemistry.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] For example, a worldwide grid of well over a million ordinary PCs was harnessed for cancer research in the project grid.org, which ended in April 2007.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/ligand-biochemistry] Grid.org has been succeeded by similar projects such as World Community Grid, Human Proteome Folding Project, Compute Against Cancer and Folding@Home.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The ultimate goal of docking is the prediction of the three-dimensional structure of the macromolecular complex of interest as it would occur in a living organism.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Docking itself only produces plausible candidate structures.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] These candidates must be ranked using methods such as scoring functions to identify structures that are most likely to occur in nature.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The term "docking" originated in the late 1970s, with a more restricted meaning; then, "docking" meant refining a model of a complex structure by optimizing the separation between the interactors but keeping their relative orientations fixed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Later, the relative orientations of the interacting partners in the modelling was allowed to vary, but the internal geometry of each of the partners was held fixed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This type of modelling is sometimes referred to as "rigid docking".
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] With further increases in computational power, it became possible to model changes in internal geometry of the interacting partners that may occur when a complex is formed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This type of modelling is referred to as "flexible docking".
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The biological roles of most proteins, as characterized by which other macromolecules they interact with, are known at best incompletely.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Even those proteins that participate in a well-studied biological process (e.g., the Krebs cycle) may have unexpected interaction partners or functions which are unrelated to that process.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] In cases of known protein–protein interactions, other questions arise.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Genetic diseases (e.g., cystic fibrosis) are known to be caused by misfolded or mutated proteins, and there is a desire to understand what, if any, anomalous protein–protein interactions a given mutation can cause.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] In the distant future, proteins may be designed to perform biological functions, and a determination of the potential interactions of such proteins will be essential.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Protein–protein docking is ultimately envisaged to address all these issues.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Furthermore, since docking methods can be based on purely physical principles, even proteins of unknown function (or which have been studied relatively little) may be docked.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The only prerequisite is that their molecular structure has been either determined experimentally, or can be estimated by a protein structure prediction technique.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Protein–nucleic acid interactions feature prominently in the living cell.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Transcription factors, which regulate gene expression, and polymerases, which catalyse replication, are composed of proteins, and the genetic material they interact with is composed of nucleic acids.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Modeling protein–nucleic acid complexes presents some unique challenges, as described below.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The first use of computers was in a study on hemoglobin interaction in sickle-cell fibres.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This was followed in 1978 by work on the trypsin-BPTI complex.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Computers discriminated between good and bad models using a scoring function which rewarded large interface area, and pairs of molecules in contact but not occupying the same space.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The computer used a simplified representation of the interacting proteins, with one interaction centre for each residue.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Favorable electrostatic interactions, including hydrogen bonds, were identified by hand.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] In the early 1990s, more structures of complexes were determined, and available computational power had increased substantially.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] With the emergence of bioinformatics, the focus moved towards developing generalized techniques which could be applied to an arbitrary set of complexes at acceptable computational cost.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The new methods were envisaged to apply even in the absence of phylogenetic or experimental clues; any specific prior knowledge could still be introduced at the stage of choosing between the highest ranking output models, or be framed as input if the algorithm catered for it.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] 1992 saw the publication of the correlation method, an algorithm which used the fast Fourier transform to give a vastly improved scalability for evaluating coarse shape complementarity on rigid-body models.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This was extended in 1997 to cover coarse electrostatics.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] In 1996 the results of the first blind trial were published, in which six research groups attempted to predict the complexed structure of TEM-1 Beta-lactamase with Beta-lactamase inhibitor protein (BLIP).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The exercise brought into focus the necessity of accommodating conformational change and the difficulty of discriminating between conformers.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] It also served as the prototype for the CAPRI assessment series, which debuted in 2001.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] If the bond angles, bond lengths and torsion angles of the components are not modified at any stage of complex generation, it is known as *rigid body docking*.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] A subject of speculation is whether or not rigid-body docking is sufficiently good for most docking.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] When substantial conformational change occurs within the components at the time of complex formation, rigid-body docking is inadequate.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] However, scoring all possible conformational changes is prohibitively expensive in computer time.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Docking procedures which permit conformational change, or *flexible docking* procedures, must intelligently select small subset of possible conformational changes for consideration.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] For many interactions, the binding site is known on one or more of the proteins to be docked.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This is the case for antibodies and for competitive inhibitors.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] In other cases, a binding site may be strongly suggested by mutagenic or phylogenetic evidence.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Configurations where the proteins interpenetrate severely may also be ruled out *a priori*.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] After making exclusions based on prior knowledge or stereochemical clash, the remaining space of possible complexed structures must be sampled exhaustively, evenly and with a sufficient coverage to guarantee a near hit.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Each configuration must be scored with a measure that is capable of ranking a nearly correct structure above at least 100,000 alternatives.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This is a computationally intensive task, and a variety of strategies have been developed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Each of the proteins may be represented as a simple cubic lattice.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Then, for the class of scores which are discrete convolutions, configurations related to each other by translation of one protein by an exact lattice vector can all be scored almost simultaneously by applying the convolution theorem.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] It is possible to construct reasonable, if approximate, convolution-like scoring functions representing both stereochemical and electrostatic fitness.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Reciprocal space methods have been used extensively for their ability to evaluate enormous numbers of configurations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] They lose their speed advantage if torsional changes are introduced.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Another drawback is that it is impossible to make efficient use of prior knowledge.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The question also remains whether convolutions are too limited a class of scoring function to identify the best complex reliably.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] In Monte Carlo, an initial configuration is refined by taking random steps which are accepted or rejected based on their induced improvement in score (see the Metropolis criterion), until a certain number of steps have been tried.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The assumption is that convergence to the best structure should occur from a large class of initial configurations, only one of which needs to be considered.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Initial configurations may be sampled coarsely, and much computation time can be saved.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Because of the difficulty of finding a scoring function which is both highly discriminating for the correct configuration and also converges to the correct configuration from a distance, the use of two levels of refinement, with different scoring functions, has been proposed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Torsion can be introduced naturally to Monte Carlo as an additional property of each random move.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Monte Carlo methods are not guaranteed to search exhaustively, so that the best configuration may be missed even using a scoring function which would in theory identify it.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] How severe a problem this is for docking has not been firmly established.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] To find a score which forms a consistent basis for selecting the best configuration, studies are carried out on a standard benchmark (see below) of protein–protein interaction cases.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Scoring functions are assessed on the rank they assign to the best structure (ideally the best structure should be ranked 1), and on their coverage (the proportion of the benchmark cases for which they achieve an acceptable result).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] It is usual to create hybrid scores by combining one or more categories above in a weighted sum whose weights are optimized on cases from the benchmark.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] To avoid bias, the benchmark cases used to optimize the weights must not overlap with the cases used to make the final test of the score.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The ultimate goal in protein–protein docking is to select the ideal ranking solution according to a scoring scheme that would also give an insight into the affinity of the complex.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Such a development would drive *in silico* protein engineering, computer-aided drug design and/or high-throughput annotation of which proteins bind or not (annotation of interactome).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Several scoring functions have been proposed for binding affinity / free energy prediction.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] However the correlation between experimentally determined binding affinities and the predictions of nine commonly used scoring functions have been found to be nearly orthogonal (R2 ~ 0).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Textual information from scientific articles can provide useful cues for scoring.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] A benchmark of 84 protein–protein interactions with known complexed structures has been developed for testing docking methods.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The set is chosen to cover a wide range of interaction types, and to avoid repeated features, such as the profile of interactors' structural families according to the SCOP database.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Benchmark elements are classified into three levels of difficulty (the most difficult containing the largest change in backbone conformation).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The protein–protein docking benchmark contains examples of enzyme-inhibitor, antigen-antibody and homomultimeric complexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The latest version of protein-protein docking benchmark consists of 230 complexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] A protein-DNA docking benchmark consists of 47 test cases.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] A protein-RNA docking benchmark was curated as a dataset of 45 non-redundant test cases with complexes solved by X-ray crystallography only as well as an extended dataset of 71 test cases with structures derived from homology modelling as well.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The protein-RNA benchmark has been updated to include more structures solved by X-ray crystallography and now it consists of 126 test cases.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The benchmarks have a combined dataset of 209 complexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] A binding affinity benchmark has been based on the protein–protein docking benchmark.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] 81 protein–protein complexes with known experimental affinities are included; these complexes span over 11 orders of magnitude in terms of affinity.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Each entry of the benchmark includes several biochemical parameters associated with the experimental data, along with the method used to determine the affinity.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This benchmark was used to assess the extent to which scoring functions could also predict affinities of macromolecular complexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] This Benchmark was post-peer reviewed and significantly expanded.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The new set is diverse in terms of the biological functions it represents, with complexes that involve G-proteins and receptor extracellular domains, as well as antigen/antibody, enzyme/inhibitor, and enzyme/substrate complexes.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] It is also diverse in terms of the partners' affinity for each other, with Kd ranging between 10−5 and 10−14 M.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Nine pairs of entries represent closely related complexes that have a similar structure, but a very different affinity, each pair comprising a cognate and a noncognate assembly.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The unbound structures of the component proteins being available, conformation changes can be assessed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] They are significant in most of the complexes, and large movements or disorder-to-order transitions are frequently observed.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The set may be used to benchmark biophysical models aiming to relate affinity to structure in protein–protein interactions, taking into account the reactants and the conformation changes that accompany the association reaction, instead of just the final product.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The Critical Assessment of PRediction of Interactions is an ongoing series of events in which researchers throughout the community try to dock the same proteins, as provided by the assessors.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Rounds take place approximately every 6 months.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Each round contains between one and six target protein–protein complexes whose structures have been recently determined experimentally.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The coordinates and are held privately by the assessors, with the cooperation of the structural biologists who determined them.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] The assessment of submissions is double blind.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] CAPRI attracts a high level of participation (37 groups participated worldwide in round seven) and a high level of interest from the biological community in general.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] Although CAPRI results are of little statistical significance owing to the small number of targets in each round, the role of CAPRI in stimulating discourse is significant.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/macromolecular-docking] (The CASP assessment is a similar exercise in the field of protein structure prediction).
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] In the fields of computational chemistry and molecular modelling, **scoring functions** are mathematical functions used to approximately predict the binding affinity between two molecules after they have been docked.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Most commonly one of the molecules is a small organic compound such as a drug and the second is the drug's biological target such as a protein receptor.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Scoring functions have also been developed to predict the strength of intermolecular interactions between two proteins or between protein and DNA.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Most scoring functions estimate some quantity related to change in Gibbs free energy in kcal/mol, so more *negative* scores indicate better docking, but not all scoring functions have their zero at $\Delta G=0$ , so the sign of the score is not necessarily meaningful.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Scoring functions are widely used in drug discovery and other molecular modelling applications.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] A potentially more reliable but much more computationally demanding alternative to scoring functions are free energy perturbation calculations.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Scoring functions are normally parameterized (or trained) against a data set consisting of experimentally determined binding affinities between molecular species similar to the species that one wishes to predict.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] The above information yields the three-dimensional structure of the complex.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Based on this structure, the scoring function can then estimate the strength of the association between the two molecules in the complex using one of the methods outlined below.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Finally the scoring function itself may be used to help predict both the binding mode and the active conformation of the small molecule in the complex, or alternatively a simpler and computationally faster function may be utilized within the docking run.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] The first three types, force-field, empirical and knowledge-based, are commonly referred to as classical scoring functions and are characterized by assuming their contributions to binding are linearly combined.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Due to this constraint, classical scoring functions are unable to take advantage of large amounts of training data.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] Since different scoring functions are relatively co-linear, consensus scoring functions may not improve accuracy significantly.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] This claim went somewhat against the prevailing view in the field, since previous studies had suggested that consensus scoring was beneficial.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] A perfect scoring function would be able to predict the binding free energy between the ligand and its target.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] But in reality both the computational methods and the computational resources put restraints to this goal.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] So most often methods are selected that minimize the number of false positive and false negative ligands.
[src:molecular-docking-deep/scoring-functions-for-docking] In cases where an experimental training set of data of binding constants and structures are available a simple method has been developed to refine the scoring function used in molecular docking.
